<TEXT>
the first national black arts festival attracted 
more than 150000 people to see and hear everything from tap dance 
to classical music to folk art and organizers say theyre already 
working on festival number two 
the 10day series of events which closed sunday with the annual 
atlanta jazz festival drew an enthusiastic response from the 
artists as well as audiences said tom cullen director of the 
fulton county arts council 
organizers had not quite expected the emotional intensity of 
the artistic interest cullen said the evidence of what this 
meant to the artists involved was really moving to me 
it was billed as the first national festival devoted to black 
artistic talent 
i think this one is outstanding because its the first black 
festival and look where it is its in atlanta said tap dancer 
louis carpenter at 76 im just glad to be a part of it 
carpenter and four other members of the copasetics the 
legendary new yorkbased tap dancing group founded in 1929 
performed on saturday to a soldout racially mixed audience of 500 
cullen whose council was the festivals primary sponsor said 
many of the audiences were multiracial 
overall the involvement of white patrons of the arts was 
pretty good since we didnt really do a lot in a special way to 
get white people to come to anything he said 
a mostly white audience of about 20000 saw black classical 
pianist leon bates perform with the atlanta symphony orchestra in a 
park july 31 evenly mixed audiences totaling about 30000 
attended the seven performances of the musical the apollo it was 
just like magic starring patti austin and peabo bryson in a 
tribute to the performers who appeared at new yorks famous apollo 
theater 
many events attracted mostly black audiences as the festival 
organizers had anticipated 
it was important to a lot of local black people to see 
enormously black audiences filling the halls it disproved a lot of 
stereotypical ideas about the cultural interest of the black 
community cullen said 
among the events that attracted large crowds was the exhibition 
of works by sculptor and printmaker elizabeth catlettmora her 
husband painter francisco mora and their son painter and 
sculptor david catlettmora and the play sisters by atlanta 
playwright marsha jackson 
cullen said a second festival in atlanta is already in the works 
the outpouring of interest and excitement was beyond anyones 
expectation he said itll take us two years to effectively 
organize another one then we might be able to do it every year 
the festival was not entirely without glitches choreographer 
george faison who won a tony award for the wiz and directed 
the festivals production of his 1981 offbroadway hit the 
apollo and miss austin had some complaints about malfunctioning 
sound equipment and inadequately rehearsed musicians 
the fox theater is a beautiful barn faison said but it 
takes technical knowhow to pull it off this is a sophisticated 
production that were trying to do on a summer stock schedule 
miss austin who ad libbed we need a new drummer after one 
muchtooslow number said the show was really in a state of 
disarray 
but she added that the production provided muchneeded stage 
experience for young performers and said she hoped the festival 
would be repeated to give these kids a chance to get work and to 
experiment 
</TEXT>
